  &lt;p id="J80vl7"&gt;Arduino’s &lt;a href="https://blog.arduino.cc/2024/07/11/kickstart-your-tech-journey-with-the-new-arduino-plug-and-make-kit/"&gt;new starter kit&lt;/a&gt; features electronic components that can be connected without having to know anything about soldering or wiring. It’s similar to &lt;a href="https://sphero.com/pages/littlebits"&gt;LittleBits’ electronic building blocks&lt;/a&gt; that make it easy for kids to learn about electronics but targets an older audience of beginners who eventually aspire to do more with an Arduino.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="EUElyA"&gt;The $87.36 &lt;a href="https://store-usa.arduino.cc/products/plug-and-make-kit?selectedStore=us"&gt;Arduino Plug and Make Kit&lt;/a&gt; comes with an &lt;a href="https://store-usa.arduino.cc/products/uno-r4-wifi"&gt;Arduino UNO R4 WiFi&lt;/a&gt; microcomputer featuring Bluetooth and its own built-in 12 x 8 LED matrix display, plus seven different Modulino components that can all be connected using cables that snap into one-way connector ports, ensuring nothing can be wired incorrectly.&lt;/p&gt;
